1
00:00:06,186 --> 00:00:09,131
When we were making
Golden Volcano,

2
00:00:09,611 --> 00:00:11,108
[Pizza-Love | Heart Disease]

3
00:00:11,108 --> 00:00:14,728
Śrīla Guru Mahārāj said …
First he kept saying,

4
00:00:14,741 --> 00:00:19,278
“Golden volcano—divine lava.”

5
00:00:19,278 --> 00:00:23,707
And then he would say,
“Is lava love?”

6
00:00:23,940 --> 00:00:27,475
Like that,
“Is lava love?”

7
00:00:27,860 --> 00:00:30,422
And then he would go on 
describing a little more,

8
00:00:30,422 --> 00:00:36,623
“Golden volcano—divine lava.
Is lava love?” And so he asked me,

9
00:00:36,623 --> 00:00:43,570
“Are there any connections
between the word ‘love’ and ‘lava’?”

10
00:00:43,570 --> 00:00:49,020
So, this is pre‒Internet, 
pre‒digital,

11
00:00:49,020 --> 00:00:51,861
when there were these things 
called libraries,

12
00:00:51,861 --> 00:00:55,600
you’ve probably read about them 
on Wikipedia.

13
00:00:55,600 --> 00:00:56,840
[Laughing]

14
00:00:56,840 --> 00:01:03,210
We lived next to a major university
with a pretty large library,

15
00:01:03,210 --> 00:01:06,050
so I went there 
and I thought,

16
00:01:06,050 --> 00:01:10,181
“I’m going to consult 
what they call ‘OED’”—

17
00:01:10,181 --> 00:01:12,970
the Oxford English Dictionary—

18
00:01:12,970 --> 00:01:16,542
it’s huge, like
each giant book volume

19
00:01:16,542 --> 00:01:20,821
for a letter, like ‘A’, ‘B’ …

20
00:01:20,821 --> 00:01:23,340
So I thought,
“I’ll look up ‘love’

21
00:01:23,340 --> 00:01:29,182
because I couldn’t find any connection
with that and ‘lava’”.

22
00:01:29,182 --> 00:01:32,542
So I find in the book,
‘L’—‘Love’,

23
00:01:32,542 --> 00:01:38,153
and it’s this book you read with
a magnifying glass, the type is very small,

24
00:01:38,153 --> 00:01:42,383
and seeing … 
going up and down the page,

25
00:01:42,383 --> 00:01:47,507
and at last it said,
“Sanskrit, from the Sanskrit

26
00:01:47,507 --> 00:01:50,953
lobha, lobhyati,

27
00:01:50,953 --> 00:02:00,543
which means ‘desire’,
like, ‘passionate desire’”.

28
00:02:00,543 --> 00:02:06,861
Like, we know, 
if you associate with Americans

29
00:02:06,861 --> 00:02:10,012
for any particular length of time,

30
00:02:10,012 --> 00:02:13,261
you’re likely to hear them 
say something like,

31
00:02:13,261 --> 00:02:16,685
“I love pizza!”

32
00:02:16,685 --> 00:02:20,535
So I can say, “Is that love?

33
00:02:20,535 --> 00:02:24,252
Pizza-love—is that love
or are we back to hankering?”

34
00:02:24,252 --> 00:02:28,880
Mundane hankering—
desire to consume something.

35
00:02:28,880 --> 00:02:32,061
When it’s pizza
we can smile and laugh about it;

36
00:02:32,061 --> 00:02:36,262
when it’s another person,
it’s not so funny,

37
00:02:36,262 --> 00:02:39,223
if you’re the one 
being consumed or devoured

38
00:02:39,223 --> 00:02:45,423
by somebody’s lust or desire
in the name of love; an attachment.

39
00:02:45,423 --> 00:02:50,950
They’re so attached 
to this consuming tendency

40
00:02:50,950 --> 00:02:52,352
that Guru Mahārāj says

41
00:02:52,352 --> 00:02:55,544
is identified in the pages
of the Bhāgavatam

42
00:02:55,544 --> 00:03:00,424
as hṛd-rogam—‘heart disease’.

43
00:03:00,424 --> 00:03:04,980
As he told that man,

44
00:03:04,980 --> 00:03:07,980
“What is the root cause 
of suffering?

45
00:03:07,980 --> 00:03:10,817
What is this heart disease?”

46
00:03:10,817 --> 00:03:15,336
This ‘I want’—thinking
if I can acquire something

47
00:03:15,336 --> 00:03:21,281
and devour that, consume that …
We’re called consumers

48
00:03:21,281 --> 00:03:24,861
all over the world;
‘Consumer Protection.’

49
00:03:24,861 --> 00:03:27,980
We’re consumers—
if I can consume something,

50
00:03:27,980 --> 00:03:32,406
I’ll find happiness 
and satisfaction, and fulfilment.

51
00:03:32,406 --> 00:03:35,640
And it’s really on the basis
of remembering

52
00:03:35,640 --> 00:03:37,329
the very high śloka,

53
00:03:37,329 --> 00:03:40,892
vikrīḍitaṁ vraja-vadhūbhir idaṁ ca viṣṇoḥ

54
00:03:40,892 --> 00:03:45,942
śraddhānvito ’nuśṛṇuyād atha varṇayed yaḥ

55
00:03:45,942 --> 00:03:51,775
bhaktiṁ parāṁ bhagavati pratilabhya kāmaṁ
[SB: 10.33.39]

56
00:03:51,775 --> 00:03:59,260
It’s so extraordinary
that in this practical dealing and situation

57
00:03:59,260 --> 00:04:01,632
that Guru Mahārāj 
would recall this śloka

58
00:04:01,632 --> 00:04:04,276
from the rāsa-līlā section,

59
00:04:04,276 --> 00:04:07,060
but use it
in practical application

60
00:04:07,060 --> 00:04:10,963
by saying
and factoring in reincarnation,

61
00:04:10,963 --> 00:04:13,540
“When I was
in the body of an elephant,

62
00:04:13,540 --> 00:04:19,219
I ate a jungle,
and that hunger wasn’t satisfied;

63
00:04:19,219 --> 00:04:22,180
and when I was in the body 
of a stool-eating pig,

64
00:04:22,180 --> 00:04:28,210
I ate a hill of stool,
and it was not satisfied.”

65
00:04:28,216 --> 00:04:33,012
And interestingly, when Guru Mahārāj
preached to this man like that,

66
00:04:33,012 --> 00:04:36,100
the man started to cry

67
00:04:36,100 --> 00:04:39,423
because he was a little embarrassed 
by what he had said before that,

68
00:04:39,423 --> 00:04:42,600
like, “What is the benefit 
of establishing some place,

69
00:04:42,600 --> 00:04:47,313
just talking about Kṛṣṇa?
Why don’t we help people?”

70
00:04:47,313 --> 00:04:51,247
And Guru Mahārāj said,
“You’ll not help them that way.

71
00:04:51,247 --> 00:05:00,507
Only by re‒purposing attachment 
will you help them.”

72
00:05:00,507 --> 00:05:03,061
So the man started to cry, 
and then he said,

73
00:05:03,061 --> 00:05:06,421
“Swamiji, I believe in God”,

74
00:05:06,430 --> 00:05:09,405
and Guru Mahārāj said,

75
00:05:09,405 --> 00:05:13,925
“Your eyes 
are the evidence of that.”

76
00:05:14,359 --> 00:05:15,795
Hare Kṛṣṇa.

